Mefisto-NLSER solves the Non-Linear Schrodinger Equation (NLSE)
in a 2d or 3d domain, with Lagrange Finite Elements
(triangles and/or quadrangles in 2d; tetrahedra, pentahedra or hexahedra in 3d)
Cf the web page https://www.ljll.math.upmc.fr/perronnet/NLSE/NLSE.html
Cf the test files nlsesqri, nlsecu, cylbreak2d, solitonsph20, nlsecuvv, nlsgpe
of $MEFISTO/testa executables by the typing of  readf FileName;

The problem is to compute the complex wave U(t,X) = V(t,X) + i W(t,X) solution
of the NLSE:

Mass i dU(t,X)/dt -Alfa Laplacian U(t,X) + N(|U|**2) U(t,X) 
   - i OmegaZ (x dU/dy - y dU/dx) = F(t,X)   in the domain

where N(|U|**2)(t,X) = Beta |U(t,X)|**2 or Beta |U(t,X)|**2 + Gama |U(t,X)|**4 or ...

with the boundary conditions
. U(t,X) = UD(t,X) on the GammaD boundary
. Alfa dU(t,X)/dn = UN(t,X) on the GammaN boundary
.-Alfa dU(t,X)/dn = g(X) ( U(t,X) - UR(t,X) ) on the GammaR boundary

and the initial conditions
U(t=t0,X) = U0  on the domain and its boundary.

One example of the user's function to define N(|U|**2) is:
DefFunc NLSECoef(t,x,y,z,ntyobj,nuobj,WaveR,WaveI);
  DefVar nlc; nlc = WaveR**2 + WaveI**2;
  NLSECoef = nlc * ( Beta + Gama * nlc );
EndFunc;
WaveR and WaveI are respectively the real and imaginary parts of the wave U(t,X)
computed at the previous iteration. Beta and Gama are user's constants.

The time integration uses a one time step, which is adapted to the wave values
along the time.

To solve the problem, it is necessary
- to have construct the mesh of the domain, an object for Mefisto and
  interpolated it with a type of Lagrange polynomials;
- to give the physical characteristics of the domain:
  mass, Alfa, N(|U|), force, boundary and initial conditions;
- to choose what problem to solve: Eigenvalues Ei Eigenvectors Ui,
  or the wave U(t,X) by a time step algorithm;
- to visualize the eigenvectors or the wave.

