2; offers the entry of data, volume by volume in 3d or surface by surface in 2d
(mass density, Alfa, user's function N(|U|), Force F, initial U,
the boundary conditions UD, UN, g, UR of surfaces, lines, points.
These data may be given by constants or functions.
Example of a definition function N(|U|):
DefFunc NLSECoef(t,x,y,z,ntyobj,nuobj,WaveR,WaveI);
  r2 = x*x + y*y;
  Vx = r2 * ( 0.5 + r2 * 0.25 );
  NLSECoef = -Vx -Beta * ( WaveR**2 + WaveI**2 );
EndFunc;

Example of a force definition function:
DefFunc ComplexForce(t,x,y,z,nutyob,nuobjt,partnb,waveRP,waveIP,zero);
  If partnb=1 then
    ComplexForce = RealForce(t,x,y,z);
  Else
    ComplexForce = ImaginaryForce(t,x,y,z);
  EndIf;
EndFunc;

The initial wave may be given by constants or functions,
or recovers as a wave among previously computed at different times;
or equal to an eigenvector previously computed as the real part of the wave.

5; IMPLICIT i dU(t)/dt -Alfa Laplacian U(t) +N(t,|U|**2)U(t)=F(t,X)
The NLSE dof the complex wave U(t,X) = V(t,X) + i W(t,X) is decomposed
in real part V and imaginary part W and the NLSE becomes
a coupled system with V and W.

Integration in time by the constant time step Euler Scheme 
    n=0  V=v0      W=w0
(3) m=0  Vn+10=Vn  Wn+10=Wn
(4)-Rho Wn+1m+1 -dt Alfa LAPLACIAN Vn+1m+1 =-Rho Wn -dt Beta (Vn+1m**2+Wn+1m**2) Vn+1m +dt Fr(t,X)
    Rho Vn+1m+1 -dt Alfa LAPLACIAN Wn+1m+1 = Rho Vn -dt Beta (Vn+1m**2+Wn+1m**2) Wn+1m +dt Fi(t,X)
    if ||Vn+1m+1-Vm n+1||>Eps||Vm n+1|| or ||Wn+1m+1-Wm n+1||>Eps||Wm+1 n+1||
    then m=m+1  go to (4)
    else Vn+1=Vn+1m+1  Wn+1=Wn+1m+1
    if TPSINI+(n+1)dt < TPSFIN then n=n+1; go to (3)
    End

In fact, at a time tn+1 and iteration m+1, the problem is to find Un+1 solution of (4)
[ K(-DeltaT (-Alfa Laplac + Beta(V0,W0));       M(Rho) ] { Vn+1 m+1 } = 
[ M(Rho)        ; K(DeltaT (-Alfa Laplac +Beta(V0,W0)) ] { Wn+1 m+1 }

{ [N(DeltaT (Beta(Vn+1m,Wn+1m)-Beta(V0,W0))] {Vn+1m} + [M(Rho)]{Wn}    } +
{ [M(Rho)]{Vn} + [N(-DeltaT (Beta(Vn+1m,Wn+1m))-Beta(V0,W0))]  {Wn+1m} }

{-DeltaT FOmegaR(tn+1,Vn+1m,Wn+1m) } + {-DeltaT FGamaR(tn+1,Vn+1m,Wn+1m) }
{ DeltaT FOmegaI(tn+1,Vn+1m,Wn+1m) }   { DeltaT FGamaI(tn+1,Vn+1m,Wn+1m) }

The IDEA is to compute ONCE the global matrice
[ K(-DeltaT (-Alfa Laplac + Beta(V0,W0));       M(Rho) ]
[ M(Rho)        ; K(DeltaT (-Alfa Laplac +Beta(V0,W0)) ]
and Crout factorize it ONCE L D Lt.
After, for every iteration m, the linear system solution is obtained
by a descent of L, a division by the diagonal matrix D and an ascent of Lt.

The given time step is the initial time step.
After the time step is adapted from the wave values along the time.
Cf testa/nlsgpe/nlsgp.imp for the data to give.

Attention, the wave may be STEADY, BLOWS UP or VANISHES...


6; i-TIME method idU(t)/dt -Alfa Laplacian U(t) +N(|U|**2)U(t)=F(t,X)
   SEMI-IMPLICIT SHEME MODIFIED in TIME with a Matrix GLOBALE nxn for
   the GROSS-PITAEVSKII equation
   n=0  V=v0      W=w0
(7)m=0  V0n+1=Vn  W0n+1=Wn

(8)(Rho/dt -LAPLACIAN/2 + ( V +N(V0**2+W0**2) ) Vn+1m+1 =
        Rho Vn/dt + OmegaZ (x dWn+1m/dy - y dWn+1m/dx) 
        -( N(Vn+1m**2+Wn+1m**2)-N(V0**2-W0**2) ) Vn+1m + Fr

   (Rho/dt -LAPLACIAN/2 + ( V +N(V0**2+W0**2) ) Wn+1m+1 =
        Rho Wn/dt - OmegaZ (x dVn+1m/dy - y dVn+1m/dx) 
        -( N(Vn+1m**2+Wn+1m**2)-N(V0**2-W0**2) ) Wn+1m + Fi

    NormL2 = (Integral |Vn+1m+1**2+Wn+1m+1**2| dX)**1/2
    Vn+1m+1 = Vn+1m+1 / NormL2, Wn+1m+1 = Wn+1m+1 / NormeL2

    If ||Vn+1m+1-Vn+1m||>Eps||Vn+1m+1|| or ||Wn+1m+1-Wn+1m||>Eps||Wn+1m+1||
    Then m=m+1  go to (8)
    Else  Vn+1=Vn+1m+1  Wn+1=Wn+1m+1
   If TPSINI+(n+1)dt < TPSFIN  then n=n+1; go to (7)
   End

Cf testa/nlsgpe/nlsgp.itime for the data to give.

11; After the computation of the wave, it is possible to visualize
either 11; its module, or 12; its real part, or 13; its imaginary part.

To see the movement, choose as zero the case number to visualize,
to see all the computed wave values during the time steps.

14; The DRAWING of STOP TEST Values of ITERATIONS shows how the wave
converge during the time iterations.

15; The DRAWING of Max|U(Node)|(Time) shows the oscillations, the increasings
or decreasings, eventually the explosions during the time.

16; It is possible to compute and draw the errors if the wave expressionis known
and the 2 following user's funtions are given:
DefFunc Exact_Real_Part(t,x,y,z);
   Exact_Real_Part = (1+t*t) * (1-x*x) * (1-y*y); { for example }
EndFunc;

DefFunc Exact_Imaginary_Part(t,x,y,z);
   Exact_Imaginary_Part = (1+t) * cos(Pis2*x) * cos(Pis2*y); { for example }
EndFunc;

